Reference-contexts: Outward-looking systems use head-mounted cameras to sight features fixed in known positions in the environment. This distinction was introduced by Gary Bishop in his 1984 dissertation <ref> [BISH84] </ref>. We restrict our discussion to systems using active beacons for features. Outward-looking systems have two significant advantages over inward-looking systems. First, outward-looking systems are more economically scalable, assuming that the beacons are less expensive than the cameras.
